üìò WEEK 4 ‚Äì DAY 2 JavaScript | Promises & Async/Await (Deep Dive)

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üéØ Goal of Day 2

‚úî Understand **asynchronous JavaScript**
‚úî Learn **Promises in depth**
‚úî Master **async / await**
‚úî Handle **errors properly**
‚úî Write **clean, real-world async code**

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üß† What is Asynchronous JavaScript?

**Asynchronous JS** allows tasks to run **without blocking** the main thread.

üìå Used for:

* API calls
* Timers
* File loading
* Database requests

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

‚è≥ Synchronous vs Asynchronous

Synchronous ‚ùå

* Tasks run **one by one**
* Slow operations block execution

Asynchronous ‚úÖ

* Long tasks run in background
* App stays responsive

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üî∑ JavaScript Promise

A **Promise** represents a value that will be available **now, later, or never**.

Promise States

1. **Pending**
2. **Fulfilled**
3. **Rejected**

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üßæ Creating a Promise

```js
const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  let success = true;

  if (success) {
    resolve("Operation successful");
  } else {
    reject("Operation failed");
  }
});
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üîó Consuming a Promise (`then`, `catch`, `finally`)

```js
promise
  .then(result => {
    console.log(result);
  })
  .catch(error => {
    console.log(error);
  })
  .finally(() => {
    console.log("Done");
  });
```

üìå

* `then()` ‚Üí success
* `catch()` ‚Üí error
* `finally()` ‚Üí always runs

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üîÅ Promise Chaining

```js
getData()
  .then(data => processData(data))
  .then(result => saveData(result))
  .catch(err => console.log(err));
```

üìå Avoids callback hell

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

‚ö†Ô∏è Callback Hell (Problem)

```js
task1(() => {
  task2(() => {
    task3(() => {
      console.log("Done");
    });
  });
});
```

‚ùå Hard to read
‚ùå Hard to debug

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

‚ö° async / await (Modern Way ‚≠ê)

`async / await` is a **cleaner way to work with Promises**.

---

üßæ Basic async / await Example

```js
async function getData() {
  return "Hello Async";
}

getData().then(console.log);
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

‚è≥ await Keyword

```js
async function fetchData() {
  let result = await promise;
  console.log(result);
}
```

üìå `await` pauses execution until Promise resolves

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üåê Real Example: Fetch API

```js
async function fetchUsers() {
  try {
    let response = await fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users");
    let data = await response.json();
    console.log(data);
  } catch (error) {
    console.log("Error:", error);
  }
}
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üö´ Error Handling with try‚Äìcatch

```js
async function test() {
  try {
    let result = await promise;
    console.log(result);
  } catch (error) {
    console.log(error);
  }
}
```

üìå Always use `try‚Äìcatch` with async/await

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üîÅ Promise vs Async/Await

| Promises         | Async/Await        |
| ---------------- | ------------------ |
| `.then()` chains | Looks synchronous  |
| Harder to read   | Cleaner & readable |
| Nested chains    | Flat structure     |

üìå **async/await preferred in modern apps**

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

‚è±Ô∏è Multiple Promises

Promise.all()

Runs promises **in parallel**.

```js
Promise.all([p1, p2, p3])
  .then(results => console.log(results));
```

üìå Fails if **any** promise fails

---

Promise.race()

Returns **first completed** promise.

```js
Promise.race([p1, p2]);
```

---

Promise.allSettled()

Returns result of **all promises**, even if failed.

```js
Promise.allSettled([p1, p2]);
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

‚ùå Common Async Mistakes

* Forgetting `await`
* Not handling errors
* Mixing `.then()` with `await`
* Blocking async code with loops

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üí° Best Practices

* Prefer `async / await`
* Always handle errors
* Use `Promise.all()` for parallel tasks
* Keep async functions small
* Avoid callback hell

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

‚úÖ DAY-2 Summary (Week-4)

* Async JavaScript basics
* Promises & states
* then / catch / finally
* async / await
* Error handling
* Promise utilities
